SIMPLE: roach
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roach
<hw>Roach</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A
cockroach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roach
<hw>Roach</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>rroche</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>reohha</ets>, D. <ets>rog</ets>, <ets>roch</ets>, G.
<ets>roche</ets>, LG. <ets>ruche</ets>, Dan. <ets>rokke</ets> ray, Sw.
<ets>rocka</ets>, and E. <ets>ray</ets> a fish.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A European fresh-water fish of the
Carp family (<spn>Leuciscus rutilus</spn>). It is silver-white, with a
greenish back.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>An American chub (<spn>Semotilus
bullaris</spn>); the fallfish.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The redfin, or
shiner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A convex curve or arch cut in the
edge of a sail to prevent chafing, or to secure a better fit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>As sound as a roach</b></col> <ety>[<ets>roach</ets>
perhaps being a corruption of a F. <ets>roche</ets> a rock]</ety>,
<cd>perfectly sound.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Roach
<hw>Roach</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to
arch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut off, as a horse's mane, so that the part left
shall stand upright.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roach-backed</ent>⟦br⟧
